## What happened

In .NET 11, **DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) was removed from macOS**. Calling `DSA.Create()` now throws on macOS — it still works on Windows and Linux.

## How to fix it

Since you need to **verify legacy DSA signatures**, you have a few options:

### Option 1 — Run verification only on Windows/Linux
If you can control where verification happens, gate DSA usage:

```csharp
if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
    throw new PlatformNotSupportedException("DSA verification not supported on macOS in .NET 11+");

using var dsa = DSA.Create();
dsa.ImportParameters(legacyPublicKey);
bool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA1);
```

### Option 2 — Migrate to a modern algorithm
If you control both signing and verification, migrate to **ECDSA** or **RSA**:

```csharp
using var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create();
var signature = ecdsa.SignData(data, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

This requires re-signing existing data with the new key.

### Option 3 — Use a cross-platform crypto library
If you must verify legacy DSA signatures on macOS, use a library like **BouncyCastle** (`Portable.BouncyCastle`) which implements DSA in managed code, independent of the OS.

**Recommendation:** For a legacy-signature-verification library that must work on all three platforms, **Option 3 (BouncyCastle)** is the most practical — it lets you keep verifying existing DSA signatures everywhere without re-signing.
